name: 4'-hydroxybiphenyl-4-carboxylic acid
Reason: The compound 4'-hydroxybiphenyl-4-carboxylic acid contains three main functional groups that influence its melting point: two phenyl rings (biphenyl), a hydroxyl (OH) group, and a carboxylic acid (COOH) group. The basic unit, biphenyl, has a typical melting point in the range of 69 to 72 degrees Celsius. The additional hydroxyl group will generally increase the melting point due to its ability to form hydrogen bonds, which requires more energy to break. This effect can be estimated to add around +100 to +150 degrees Celsius. The carboxylic acid group can also form hydrogen bonds and usually increases the melting point by a similar amount as the hydroxyl group, so we could estimate an additional +100 to +150 degrees Celsius as well. Considering these two additive effects from hydroxyl and carboxylic acid, the estimated increase in melting point would be in the range of +200 to +300 degrees Celsius to the base melting point of biphenyl.
Prediction: Starting from a base of around 70 degrees Celsius for biphenyl, and adding the effects of the hydroxyl and the carboxylic acid groups, the predicted melting point would be between 270 (70 + 200) and 370 (70 + 300) degrees Celsius.
